<Base title="Roleplay games - vals.quest">
  <h1>Roleplay games</h1>
  <p>I'm keen to organise tabletop RPG sessions and to GM, especially if someone else would be willing to GM another time.</p>
  <p>The classic introductory RPG offer is a one-shot with no rules or light rules. You can do short sessions of 2-3 hours but 3-4 hours is more typical.</p>
  <p>I have a preference for groups of 3-5 players (limit 6). For 7+ people, something like a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murder_mystery_game">murder party</a> works better than classic tabletop RPG.</p>
  <p>I enjoy introducing new players to RPGs, but I'd also be curious to run something more complex if people want to level up (it trains rationality, apparently &mdash; it's a bit like nailing the scenarios in Paleo on the first try).</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Systems I can GM</h2>

  <h3>Call of Cthulhu (intro) &mdash; mystery, horror, investigation</h3>
  <p>An RPG that starts a bit fantastical and quickly goes into cosmic horror. (Well, if you end up mad, maybe you were mad all along?)</p>
  <blockquote>In Call of Cthulhu, you take on the role of everyday people who become investigators of the unknown &mdash; whether they are prepared or not. The mysterious places, people, and situations you encounter are often not what they seem &mdash; you and your friends are the only thing standing in the way of diabolical cults and cosmic monsters from beyond space!</blockquote>
  <p>So investigate, investigate &mdash; you might survive.</p>

  <h3>Shadow Musketeers (intro) &mdash; adventure, panache, bravery, investigation</h3>
  <p>In 1654, an alien spaceship crashes in the woods of Fontainebleau, carrying dangerous convicts from across the galaxy. Regent Mazarin seizes the affair, makes a pact with the alien ship commander, and creates an elite unit: the Shadow Musketeers. You play swashbucklers blending bravery and panache to track down the most incongruous aliens &mdash; like Men in Black, but in the age of musketeers.</p>

  <h3>Ars Magica (intro) &mdash; adventure, strategy/tactics</h3>
  <p>Set in mythical Arthurian medieval Europe (where Arthurian legends and similar myths are more or less true), centered around a Covenant &mdash; a kind of school of magic with labs and advanced studies. Characters are often a mix of mages, companions, and mundane folk, seeking to grow their covenant by solving local problems or seeking precious resources.</p>

  <h3>Orc Invasion (intro)</h3>
  <p>We play as ourselves, in the 21st century, but strange things start happening... (It could be an orc invasion, literally orcs opening a portal from another world, or it could be something fantastical or Narnia-like or...)</p>

  <h3>Shadowrun (medium/complex)</h3>
  <blockquote>Shadowrun is a science fantasy tabletop role-playing game set in an alternate future in which cybernetics, magic and fantasy creatures co-exist. It combines genres of cyberpunk, urban fantasy, and crime, with occasional elements of conspiracy, horror, and detective fiction.</blockquote>

  <hr />

  <h2>Systems I'd like to try GMing</h2>

  <h3>Paranoia &mdash; science fiction, survival, dark humour</h3>
  <p>You are aboard a spaceship that has left Earth. The Computer takes care of you. It gives you your missions and responsibilities on board. Be sure to report traitor commie-mutants at every opportunity.</p>

  <h3>Star Wars</h3>

  <h3>Science fiction based on one of my dreams</h3>
  <p>You wake up in an abandoned train, or a hangar, or something. You have some memories of who you are but not much more than that. The goal is to figure out where you are, who you are, and what's going on.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Glossary</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>RPG</strong> &mdash; tabletop role-playing game (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tabletop_role-playing_game">Wikipedia</a>)</li>
    <li><strong>GM</strong> &mdash; Game Master, the person who runs the game</li>
  </ul>
</Base>
